<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-550-741  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 550 741.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  Oct 29 1990 v7 n42 p4(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Cahners-Ziff Publishing Associates LP 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>NLI updates front-end interface tool for databases; beefs upreport-writing capabilities, system links. (Natural LanguageInc.'s Natural Language 4.0 database software) (productannouncement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ballou, Melinda-Carol.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Natural Language Inc introduces Natural Language 4.0 graphicaluser interface, priced between $5,000 and $93,000 depending on theCPU.andP;  The product is designed as a front-end interface tool fordata base management systems, enabling users to access and analyzesystems through English-language commands.andP;  The updated packagefeatures Intelligent Connector, a programming tool set with awindowing environment that helps users create, test and debugNatural Language applications.andP;  Natural Language 4.0 alsoincorporates improved report-writing capabilities and anapplication programming interface linking the program to otherinterfaces and database programs.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Natural Language Inc. (Product introduction).andO;Product:   Natural Language 4.0 (Natural language user interface) (Productintroduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionNatural Language InterfacesData Base Management SystemsApplications Programming InterfaceData Base Servers.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>NLI updates front-end interface tool for databases; beefs up report-writingcapabilities, system linksandM;BERKELEY, Calif.andP;  -- Natural Language Inc. (NLI) is now shipping version 4.0of Natural Language, a database tool that allows users to access and analyzedatabase management systems via English commands.andM;Natural Language version 4.0 includes a development tool and an applicationprogramming interface (API) that integrates Natural Language with otherinterfaces and database tools.andP;  Version 4.0 also includes enhancedreport-writing capabilities.andM;The Intelligent Connector (ICon), Natural Language's development tool, is awindow-based tool set that replaces NLI Connector.andM;ICon lets users build, test and debug Natural Language applications.andP;  Itincorporates a database schema into Natural Language, NLI officials said,then lets users describe relations, attributes, mapping and other informationvia four windows.andM;&quot;ICon is a graphical environment that shows the mapping and other connectionsinvolved with building applications,&quot; said Paul Ricci, vice president ofmarketing at NLI.andM;&quot;It also prompts and coaches the user--it's an intelligent environment thatunderstands the process and tries to correct you if you make mistakes,&quot; Riccisaid.andM;&quot;Users have found their productivity [is] improved about 50 percent at ourbeta sites and training courses because they have a clearer conceptualunderstanding of the semantic connections involved with Natural Language,&quot; hesaid.andM;ICon offers automated error checking and correction.andP;  It generates an Englishdescription of the database and is compatible with the Open SoftwareFoundation's Motif graphical user interface, Open Look and DECwindows.andM;Version 4.0's API lets Natural Language be integrated with other interfacetools.andP;  &quot;The API can integrate to anything that can be called by Cfunctions,&quot; he said.andP;  &quot;We wanted Natural Language to...be a component of theuser interface.&quot;andM;Natural Language version 4.0 also features shared memory so the product'svirtual image and all application-specific information can be shared bymultiple users.andM;Version 4.0's Automated Data Extracts lets users download a data subset fromthe database server to the Natural Language client, and lets users moreeasily customize their reports.andM;Version 4.0 of Natural Language is now available.andP;  Prices range from $5,000to $93,000 depending on CPU.andM;The product now runs on IBM RISC System/6000-series machines, databasesrunning AIX and DB2 using the AIX Viaduct bridge, officials said.andP;  It alsoruns on DEC's VAX and RISC platforms and 80386 machines, Sun workstations,and Hewlett-Packard 9000-series 800 workstations.andM;For additional information, Natural Language Inc. can be contacted at 2910Seventh St., Berkeley, CA 94710, (415) 841-3628.andO;</TEXT></DOC>